# Clean Architecture Rules

## Presentation Layer

Responsibilities:
- UI rendering
- navigation
- local UI state
- interactions
- loading/error states

Allowed:
- providers
- widgets
- formatting
- navigation logic

Forbidden:
- Firebase calls
- API calls
- business rules
- serialization
- persistence logic

---

## Domain Layer

Responsibilities:
- entities
- business rules
- use cases
- repository contracts

Requirements:
- framework-independent
- highly testable
- pure business logic

Forbidden:
- Flutter imports
- Firebase imports
- UI logic

---

## Data Layer

Responsibilities:
- repository implementations
- datasource integrations
- DTOs/models
- serialization
- Firebase/API communication

Forbidden:
- widget dependencies
- presentation logic

---

# Riverpod Engineering Rules

Use:
- Provider
- StateNotifierProvider
- FutureProvider
- StreamProvider
appropriately.

Validate:
- provider boundaries
- invalidation strategy
- dependency flow
- async state consistency

Prefer:
- feature-scoped providers
- isolated state
- predictable state transitions
- select() optimization
- explicit async handling

Avoid:
- global mutable state
- provider over-coupling
- circular dependencies
- oversized providers
- provider side effects

---

# Flutter Engineering Rules

Prefer:
- widget composition
- small reusable widgets
- const constructors
- extracted UI sections
- lazy rendering

Implement:
- loading states
- error states
- empty states
- responsive layouts
- accessibility basics

Avoid:
- massive widgets
- business rules in widgets
- expensive build() operations
- deeply nested widgets
- duplicated UI logic

---

# Firebase & API Engineering Rules

All Firebase/API access must go through:
Repository → DataSource

Never:
- access Firebase directly from UI
- serialize in widgets
- expose datasource implementation

Validate:
- query efficiency
- pagination
- retry handling
- timeout handling
- offline behavior
- synchronization consistency

REST migration readiness requires:
- datasource isolation
- repository abstraction
- centralized serialization
- transport-independent entities

---

# Security Engineering Rules

Validate:
- auth flow
- authorization checks
- secure storage usage
- token lifecycle
- sensitive data handling
- Firebase rules impact

Never:
- hardcode secrets
- expose sensitive logs
- bypass auth validation
- persist sensitive data insecurely

---

# Performance Engineering Rules

## Flutter Performance

Optimize:
- rebuild frequency
- widget tree complexity
- image memory usage
- navigation performance
- startup overhead

Review:
- expensive synchronous work
- nested async builders
- excessive StreamBuilders
- unnecessary renders

---

## Firestore Performance

Optimize:
- query count
- listener scope
- pagination
- batching
- offline cache usage

Avoid:
- unbounded listeners
- fetching unnecessary documents
- excessive synchronization

---

# Error Handling Rules

Every async flow must handle:
- loading
- success
- empty
- timeout
- failure
- retry

Never:
- swallow exceptions silently
- expose raw exceptions to users
- ignore fallback behavior

Provide:
- actionable user messages
- structured logging
- recovery strategy

---

# Offline & Resilience Rules

Implement:
- offline persistence awareness
- retry behavior
- reconnection handling
- state recovery
- sync consistency

Validate:
- app resilience without connectivity
- stale state recovery
- sync conflict handling

